nps_rationale:
I rate this caller as neutral/Passive (7). The call is primarily a routine payment attempt—caller confirms they were "trying to make the payment for your, for your mobile phone, the $30.55" ('And uh, yes, oh, uh, were you trying to make the payment for your, for your mobile phone, the $30.55?') which establishes a baseline expectation of service (lines 24-25). The agent proceeds to take the card and attempts the charge ('OK, I'm going to run that card for exactly $30.55.'), but the transaction is declined ('I got a.' / 'It won't work. It's an unlucky.' / 'Yeah, I got a decline.') which is a negative operational outcome that could lower satisfaction (lines 62-77). However, the caller's comments are mostly personal distress about a stolen purse and non-attributable beliefs ('They stole my purse... The Anunnaki have gotten in here and stolen my purse.' and 'So I'm under siege by the Anunnaki and I there's nothing I can do but die. I'm sorry. Thanks for helping. Goodbye.'), not explicit criticism of Spectrum's service, so there is no clear hostile sentiment toward the company itself (lines 29-36, 81). Because the call ends without clear blame or enthusiastic praise for Spectrum, the overall effect if shared would be unlikely to promote or strongly detract from Spectrum—consistent with a neutral/passive rating (7). Citations: payment attempt ('were you trying to make the payment for your, for your mobile phone, the $30.55?'), card processing and decline ('OK, I'm going to run that card for exactly $30.55.'; 'It won't work.'; 'I got a decline.'), and caller distress that is non-company-directed ('They stole my purse... The Anunnaki...'; 'there's nothing I can do but die. I'm sorry. Thanks for helping. Goodbye.')."  ,
  "citations": [24, 25, 62, 76, 77, 29, 81]
}

The caller expresses clear frustration with the ordering and pricing process, saying it is “stupid” ('I think it's just stupid so I'm changing my mind' - line 30) and that it’s “so frustrating” to jump through hoops to lower the bill ('It's so frustrating that you gotta get all these stupid things in order to get your Bill down' - line 33). She explicitly compares Spectrum unfavorably to a competitor and is price-driven, noting Verizon can get her to $50 ('I'm used to paying $50.00 and Verizon' - line 28; 'Verizon is offering something for $50.00' - line 29) and asking Spectrum to keep the bill low ('But you guys keep it down a little bit please for granny' - line 47). The agent attempts to help by cancelling the TV order and transferring her to customer solutions ('let me see if i can cancel this order' - line 31; 'let's get you over to our customer Solutions Group' - line 51), but the caller’s negative sentiments and intent to consider a competitor indicate a negative post-call view of Spectrum overall. Therefore the caller is a detractor with mild-to-moderate negativity rather than extreme hostility. Citations: ('I think it's just stupid so I'm changing my mind' - 30), ('It's so frustrating that you gotta get all these stupid things in order to get your Bill down' - 33), ('I'm used to paying $50.00 and Verizon' - 28), ('Verizon is offering something for $50.00' - 29), ('But you guys keep it down a little bit please for granny' - 47), ('let me see if i can cancel this order' - 31), ('let's get you over to our customer Solutions Group' - 51)."  ,
  "citations": [30,33,28,29,47,31,51]
}

The caller was concerned about a scam and appreciated the agent's help, which leaves them mildly positive but not enthusiastic. The agent reassured her it was likely a scam: ('that wouldn't have been us. That sounds more like a scam call 'cause we don't call you and ask for your credit card number.') (27). The agent documented the report: ('Oh no, absolutely. I can put it in the notes on your account too.') (36), showing helpful service. The agent offered a lower-cost TV option and concrete savings: ('I have a, uh, TV package called the TV choice 15 and that would give you all your local channels and then you get to select fifteen additional channels... that would drop your bill down... to 85') (91), indicating a beneficial outcome. The caller thanked the agent and expressed appreciation: ('Okie Dokie, appreciate you. You're very nice.') (154). The agent closed positively summarizing the help: ('We went over the Choice 15 plan in your account. I just want to thank you for calling in today and let me assist with answering your questions.') (157). Overall the interaction likely increases her satisfaction somewhat but does not show the strong enthusiasm or explicit recommendation required for a Promoter, so she is a Passive (8).",
  "citations": [27, 36, 91, 154, 157]
}

The caller began with a problem: they said they were "having trouble" and trying to set up an account for automatic payment ('"And I I'm having trouble."' [5]) and had difficulty "getting her an account set up online" ('"Logging getting her an account set up online, or otherwise getting it set up"' [6]). The agent completed the requested tasks and recapped that the online account, username, temporary password, and autopay setup instructions were provided ('"So just a quick recap of the call. We set up an online account. You have the username, the temporary password... and then you'll be setting up autopay"' [101]). The caller confirmed receipt of the verification email and acknowledged success ('"Yes, I got got something headed paying your Bill with my spectrum app."' [105]) and exchanged polite thanks at the end ('"Thank you."' [109]; '"Thank you. Goodbye."' [111]). Overall, the interaction resolved the issue and left the caller satisfied but not effusively enthusiastic, so this maps to a mild positive / Passive score of 8 under the rubric. (Evidence: lines 5-6, 101, 105, 109, 111.)"  ,
  "citations": [5, 6, 101, 105, 109, 111]
}

Caller asked about a senior discount ('Yes i was wondering if there would be some kind of a senior discount that i could get on my Bill.'), but the agent confirmed Louisiana does not offer a state senior discount ('OK States no ma'am louisiana is not One of the States that offer a senior discount.'). The agent clearly explained the current promotion and that the promotional price will increase soon ('that's because the internet they have you on yes is a $90.00 internet and spectrum is paying 20. Dollars and a Penny of it until. July.'; 'you're going to have that for another month and then you'll go to 8499?'), and the caller expressed that the outcome wasn’t helpful ('But it don't help me Michelle') while remaining polite and appreciative of the agent's effort ('Well then thank you Michelle i appreciate your effort honey'). Overall the interaction leaves the customer mildly dissatisfied with their pricing outcome but not actively hostile; if shared it would be unlikely to promote Spectrum and only mildly negative, matching a neutral/passive stance after the call ended. ('Yes i was wondering if there would be some kind of a senior discount that i could get on my Bill.', 'OK States no ma'am louisiana is not One of the States that offer a senior discount.', 'you're going to have that for another month and then you'll go to 8499?', 'But it don't help me Michelle', 'Well then thank you Michelle i appreciate your effort honey')."  ,
  "citations": [4, 28, 54, 60, 63, 71]
}

The caller described a billing surprise and financial hardship: she said she had explained she was laid off and wanted to discontinue TV but keep Internet ('I spoke to someone last month about my bill and I explained to him that I was laid off from my job and that what I would be discontinuing my umm just the TV portion of my service but keeping my Internet.' - line 2) and noted the bill unexpectedly rose ('now it seems like it went up.' - line 5). The agent clearly explained the cause as an expired promotion ('the increase was due to a promotional discount that you had on your TV portion that you no longer have.' - line 16; 'you had a promotional discount on the Internet of $14.00 that expired' - line 24), which shows the issue was understood. Importantly, the agent offered to escalate and remove the TV so future bills won’t include it ('I'm just going to place you on a brief hold so that when my account specialist can get that TV removed for you. So going forward you won't be charged for it, OK?' - line 52) and the caller accepted ('OK. Thank you.' - line 53). Overall the caller experienced a negative surprise but received a helpful resolution offer; this is unlikely to make her a promoter but she appears satisfied enough after the interaction to remain passive rather than a detractor ('I thought they wrote the notes and everything to, to do that, but then I, I got, I received the bill and then I see the it's increased so.' - line 38). Therefore a score of 8 (mild positive/ satisfied but not enthusiastic) best fits the post-call sentiment toward Spectrum given the partial resolution and remaining inconvenience ('I guess I missed the window again.' - line 29)."  ,
  "citations": [2,5,16,24,52,53,38,29]
}

The caller left satisfied but not effusively enthusiastic, so this is a 'Passive' outcome. The agent provided clear next steps and a process for resolving the fraud: the agent explained the online form and site ('OK so it's www.spectrum.net.'), required documents ('A photocopy of of course his government issued ID and then proof of residency'), and the expected timeline ('this could take 15 Days to complete with our investigation Team') (lines 54, 62, 65). The caller accepted the resolution and expressed agreement: 'OK yeah that's that'll work OK' and thanked the agent ('Yes, yeah. Me too. Thank you.') indicating mild positive sentiment but not strong advocacy (lines 73, 80). Overall, this call would not strongly promote Spectrum to others but also would not detract from the brand — it leaves the customer mildly positive, matching a score of 8. (Cited evidence: 'OK so it's www.spectrum.net.'; 'A photocopy of of course his government issued ID and then proof of residency'; 'this could take 15 Days to complete with our investigation Team'; 'OK yeah that's that'll work OK'; 'Yes, yeah. Me too. Thank you.') (lines 54, 62, 65, 73, 80). Various procedural clarifications and the agent's closing politeness ('OK so i thank you for being patient with me...') also support a calm, resolved outcome (line 79). The call therefore results in a Passive (8)." ,
  "citations": [54, 62, 65, 73, 80, 79]
}

The caller presented a billing problem—"'Your service was your service was cut off today umm due to non payment of $179.46'" ('Your service was your service was cut off today umm due to non payment of $179.46.' - line 44) and confusion about unexpected charges such as a cable box they say they don't have ("I do not have…a TV box" - line 54) and a bounced payment that increased the balance ("A check was written umm actually ... it wasn't a good check" - line 100 and "you went from only having $29.75 as a balance to $401.16" - line 121 / 103). The agent clearly explained fees and options and processed an on-call payment to restore service ("For the payment amount of 17946...Their payment is processing...Perfect your services will be restored uh within an hour." - lines 162, 164, 177), and the caller responded politely and committed to pay the remaining balance by the due date ("I'm gonna try to do it on June 3rd so it won't go higher." - line 182). Overall the interaction resolved the immediate issue but revolved around billing frustration rather than strong enthusiasm for the brand; if shared, this call would not promote Spectrum strongly but it is satisfactory — consistent with a Passive score (8)."  ,
  "citations": [44, 54, 61, 100, 103, 162, 164, 177, 182, 184]
}

The caller is clearly dissatisfied and likely to leave Spectrum after the call. They say they had service outages and the agent found only a small outage credit: "it is offering umm Credit for those 2 Days it's $7.21" ('"it is offering umm Credit for those 2 Days it's $7.21 that will be credited for the outage."' - line 35) and the caller immediately responds that "it needs to be i think more than that because my Bill is $200.00 a month." ('"Uh it needs to be i think more than that because my Bill is $200.00 a month."' - line 36). The customer states cost pressure and intent to switch: "we're probably gonna switch to them 'cause their rates are a lot cheaper." ('"we're probably gonna switch to them 'cause their rates are a lot cheaper."' - line 45) and reiterates dissatisfaction: "I'm just not happy so unless they can extend our Bill i I'm just gonna probably from somewhere else to go." ('"Yeah I'm just not happy so unless they can extend our Bill i I'm just gonna probably from somewhere else to go."' - line 66). The agent is sympathetic but explicitly limited in remedies: "i am Limited in my power" ('"It's understandable II wish there was a a One that i could fix these but umm i am Limited in my power"' - line 67), indicating the call is unlikely to change the customer's negative view. Taken together, this would likely detract from Spectrum (moderately negative sentiment with concrete intent to leave). Overall score: 3 (moderately negative)."  ,
  "citations": [35, 36, 45, 66, 67]
}

The caller was initially confused and frustrated about billing ("Because at one point it said I didn't owe anything after I made those payments and then now I owe a whole bunch. So I'm just very confusing on my billing." (43)) and found the app unclear ("I'm looking at the app, it's kind of confusing with how it operates." (61)). The agent clarified the returned payments and the current amount due ("So the past due amount right now for the May portion is $54.75" (57)) and confirmed the exact amount to pay, after which the caller agreed to pay and thanked the agent ("But it says past due balance 54 so I was just confused. So I just need to pay the 5475." (63); "Correct." (64); "OK, then I'll do that right now." (65); "That's it. Thank you so much." (67)). Overall the issue was resolved during the call but the customer's tone reflected lingering confusion rather than enthusiasm, so the caller is more likely a Passive (score 7) rather than a Promoter or Detractor. ('Because at one point it said I didn't owe anything after I made those payments and then now I owe a whole bunch. So I'm just very confusing on my billing.' (43)) ('I'm looking at the app, it's kind of confusing with how it operates.' (61)) ('But it says past due balance 54 so I was just confused. So I just need to pay the 5475.' (63)) ('Correct.' (64)) ('OK, then I'll do that right now.' (65)) ('That's it. Thank you so much.' (67)) ('So the past due amount right now for the May portion is $54.75' (57)) .",
  "citations": [43, 61, 57, 63, 64, 65, 67]
}

The caller is clearly dissatisfied and unresolved about a billing dispute: they state they "sent in a letter to customer service for about 3 weeks ago" and that "spectrum was saying that i owed them $500.00 and i came up with spectrum owed me $300.00" ("sent in a letter...3 weeks ago" (6); "spectrum was saying that i owed them $500.00 and i came up with spectrum owed me $300.00" (7)). They report not hearing back and lack of records: the agent confirms uncertainty that "they had closed the case number on 522" and that there is "no ma'am i just see the collections coming in here and the payment services Team" ("closed the case number on 522" (71); "no ma'am i just see the collections coming in here" (73)). The agent only issued a new ticket and noted a small partial credit of "$29.00" while the rest of the adjustment is still pending ("they did give some type of small adjustment heroes $29.00" (33); "we are still waiting on the rest of that adjustment so what I'm going to do here is place another ticket" (34-35)). Although the agent was polite and the caller concedes she will "wait for the call" ("OK alright i'll wait for the call thank you." (74)), the core issue remains unresolved and the caller expresses frustration and potential harm to her perception of Spectrum. Overall this call would likely detract from Spectrum rather than promote it, so I assign a negative but not extreme score of 4 based on unresolved billing and slow follow-up evidence (6,7,71,33-35,74)." ,
  "citations": [6, 7, 71, 73, 33, 34, 35, 74]
}

The caller's issue was resolved and they expressed appreciation, indicating mild positive sentiment toward Spectrum. The agent clarified the balance was for Internet and that mobile showed a $0.00 plan ('OK, Yeah, it does look like that is for, um, Internet services.' (11); 'for mobile I'm seeing a $0.00 balance' (12)), the agent explained billing timing and fees ('So the 9396 that is, yes, for the Internet... your normal bill will be the 6396' (19)), and provided a built-in grace period which the caller accepted ('Looks like you have until June 10th before any interruption occurs.' (22); 'oh, OK, that's perfect and I appreciate it.' (23)). The agent also resolved the outdated phone number in the account and the caller thanked them ('So it has been adjusted...' (36); 'Alright, just find that I appreciate it.' (41)). The call ended politely with no lingering frustration ('Uh, no. That'll be all. Thank you.' (43); 'Alright, you too. Bye bye.' (45)). Overall the interaction left the caller satisfied but not enthusiastically promotive, so I rate them an 8 (mild positive / Passive)."  ,
  "citations": [11, 12, 19, 22, 23, 36, 41, 43, 45]
}

Caller left satisfied and polite after the agent confirmed the scheduling and payment details: agent explained scheduling and expectations ('Yeah, that's perfectly fine. That is within the range. Just know that you are still going to go get those texts and calls.' - Agent, line 22) and the caller agreed to pay the past due amount ('Oh, Asus. Oh, OK, OK, fine. I'll pay that then.' - Caller, line 25). The caller explicitly thanked the agent and said they were helped ('Uh, no. You've been a big help. Thank you so much, ma'am.' - Caller, line 28) and closed the call warmly ('You too. Thanks again.' - Caller, line 30). These indicate mild positive sentiment and likely no strong advocacy, so the caller is best classified as a Passive (8)."  ,
  "citations": [22, 25, 28, 30]
}

The caller expresses clear negative sentiment about Spectrum pricing and is considering cancelling service: she says "I can't afford this" (line 19) and later "OK, I'll be calling you back to see what to cancel" (line 30). She also indicates surprise and frustration about unexpected charges: "I've only been paying for the mobile service and the internet was free" (line 9) and reacts to the total monthly cost: "Total balance is $90.00 a month" (line 27). These statements show a mild-to-moderate negative view that would likely detract from Spectrum if shared with others, so I rate this a 4 under the rubric for mild-to-moderate negative sentiment. Citations: ('I can't afford this'), ('OK, I'll be calling you back to see what to cancel'), ('I've only been paying for the mobile service and the internet was free'), ('Total balance is $90.00 a month')." ,
  "citations": [19, 30, 9, 27]
}

The caller decided to keep Spectrum Internet but cancel TV due to cost, indicating a practical choice rather than enthusiasm or strong dislike ("Let's do that. Just cancel everything. Except the the $35 for Internet.") (lines 121-122, 135). The agent successfully clarified billing and next steps, and the caller expressed gratitude and understanding ("I really appreciate everything that you've done" and "you were very precise and straightforward that I understand everything now"), which improves the caller's post-call view (lines 162, 166-167). There is some frustration about price increases and non-proration of bills ("Spectrum does not prorate... we are still charged for the full..."), showing mild negative sentiment about cost but not about the brand or agent (line 146), so the overall sentiment is mildly positive/neutral — a Passive (8). Each claim is grounded in the transcript: decision to cancel TV/keep Internet ('"Let's do that. Just cancel everything. Except the the $35 for Internet."' — lines 121-122, 135), appreciation for the agent and clarity ('"I really appreciate everything that you've done"' — line 162; '"you were very precise and straightforward that I understand everything now"' — lines 166-167), and concern about billing/proration ('"Spectrum does not prorate... we are still charged for the full..."' — line 146). This call is unlikely to actively promote Spectrum but also unlikely to lead the caller to strongly disparage the brand — fitting a Passive rating (8)."  ,
  "citations": [121, 122, 135, 162, 166, 167, 146]
}

The caller expresses clear frustration and distrust toward Spectrum, indicating a negative view that would likely detract from the brand. Evidence: the caller complains about unexpected charges ('"I get AI get a Bill in the mail says i have to pay 205"' — line 5) and confusion over payments ('"Umm i paid what they wanted me to pay."' — line 22). They explicitly accuse the company of bad intent ('"I think you guys are just trying to screw me."' — line 35) and emphasize financial hardship with repeated unwanted contact ('"i keep getting phone calls... well you know what I'm on a fixed income i don't get paid till the first."' — line 46). Although the agent explains billing details and attempted credits ('"we've actually applied some credits to your account."' — line 40) the caller remains upset and feels burdened by automated calls and past-due requirements ('"we need a payment of $308.47 on or before June 3rd"' — line 47), supporting a negative post-call NPS. Overall this would likely lead the caller to speak poorly of Spectrum, so I rate them a detractor (3)."  } ,
  "citations": [5, 22, 35, 46, 40, 47]
}

The caller expresses strong negative feelings and intentions to leave Spectrum and even sue after feeling overcharged and misled. She says the agent “took it off” and that it was “a terrible thing to do, really bad” ('It didn't fall off. They took it off... it was a terrible thing to do, really bad.' - lines 41) and explicitly calls the action “cheating me” ('That's nasty. It was cheating me.' - line 42). She threatens to switch providers ('And I think I will probably go to T mobile after this.' - line 44) and later says she believes she has grounds for legal action ('I think I have a lawsuit against Spectrum.' - line 117). She also details being charged for unused equipment ('So by switching me and continuing to charge me for the boxes... Spectrum charged me double.' - lines 100, 103). These comments indicate strong dissatisfaction that would likely detract from Spectrum if shared, so I rate this a detractor with a score of 2 ('Spectrum charged me double.' - line 103; 'I think I have a lawsuit against Spectrum.' - line 117)."  ,
  "citations": [41, 42, 44, 100, 103, 117]
}

The caller expresses clear dissatisfaction with Spectrum and indicates they may leave the service. They complain about an unresolved balance and inability to reduce it: ('So there's nothing I can do. You can't lower it or anything. I'm still going to have to pay that 300 Bucks.') (18). They call the TV product poor: ('My TV service was crappy.') (19). They compare competitor pricing favorably and note neighbors already switched: ('we've got the highest internet... I get my phone and everything for under $100.00... $94.00. For everything.') (21-23) and ('there's been 3 of our neighbors already that's already disconnected and gone with Kinetic. So I don't know how you stay in Business.') (24). The agent confirms the balance and that the caller must still pay, which likely reinforces the negative outcome: ('The remaining balance on the account is $300.00.') (17) and ('You would have still have to pay it.') (25). Overall tone and statements would likely detract from Spectrum if shared with others, so this maps to a Detractor (score 3)." ,
  "citations": [18, 19, 21, 22, 23, 24, 17, 25]
}

The caller's issue was resolved during the call and they expressed satisfaction but not strong enthusiasm. They explicitly confirmed they wanted to pay the bill ('13182 that's the full Bill payment correct.' (line 54)) and the agent completed the transaction ('so that went through' (line 59)). The caller indicated a simple outcome-focused satisfaction: 'II don't need it as Long as it's on my card then I'm good as Long as it's paid I'm good.' (line 60). The agent closed courteously thanking the customer for being with Spectrum ('i want to thank you for being a part of spectrum' (line 61)), and the caller thanked the agent in return ('Yes ma'am thank you very much.' (line 117); 'Umm no ma'am that's it thank you so much.' (line 115)). Taken together, these show mild positive sentiment and a satisfied but not enthusiastic likelihood to actively promote Spectrum, which fits the Passive category (score 8). Citations: lines 54, 59, 60, 61, 115, 117 were primary evidence for this assessment." ,
  "citations": [54, 59, 60, 61, 115, 117]
}

The caller expresses clear anger and intent to defect after an unresolved billing/line issue. They describe the core problem as a miscommunication about a free line being added as a third line: ('he said He was giving us a free line, which I thought was.' ) (lines 9) and ('But we don't need the third line.') (line 11). The agent explains removing the third line would require returning the phone and immediate financing payment ('if we get that third line taken off, we have financing on it. And so it would become the financing for the phone would be due immediately.') (line 66), which escalates the caller's frustration. The caller uses profanity and threatens switching providers ('What a motherfuckers. Alright, I guess Verizon might be a way to go, huh?') (line 69) and accuses the company of taking advantage ('let's take advantage of old people kind of crap.') (line 71). The caller also directly insults the agent ('I hope you can suck ass the rest of the day.') (line 79). These statements indicate strong negative sentiment toward Spectrum and a high likelihood of detracting from the brand if shared, so the score is a low detractor rating of 2. Each claim above is supported by the cited lines from the transcript ('he said He was giving us a free line, which I thought was.' (9); 'But we don't need the third line.' (11); 'if we get that third line taken off...it would become the financing for the phone would be due immediately.' (66); 'What a motherfuckers...Verizon might be a way to go, huh?' (69); 'let's take advantage of old people kind of crap.' (71); 'I hope you can suck ass the rest of the day.' (79))." ,
  "citations": [9, 11, 66, 69, 71, 79]
}

The caller had a smooth, successful interaction and expressed clear satisfaction. The agent confirmed the order and price: 'i am going ahead and submitting this order to add MGM plus to your account it'll be $8.00 per month' ('Alright i appreciate your patience...' - line 28), and the caller responded appreciatively: 'No he done great thank you so much for taking care of me.' (line 32). The caller also closed the call positively: 'Oh oh I'm pretty sure thank you so much and you have a good day.' (line 34). These statements show strong positive sentiment and likelihood to speak well of Spectrum after the call, meriting a Promoter-level score of 9. Citations: 'i am going ahead and submitting this order to add MGM plus to your account it'll be $8.00 per month' (line 28); 'No he done great thank you so much for taking care of me.' (line 32); 'Oh oh I'm pretty sure thank you so much and you have a good day.' (line 34); initial agent greeting showing helpful intent: 'Thank you for choosing spectrum my name is Brandon...' (line 1). Each cited line supports the positive resolution and the caller's gratitude, indicating a favorable post-call view of Spectrum." ,
  "citations": [28, 32, 34, 1, 33]
}
